If you are dealing with arrays, you can use [System.arraycopy()][1] for that. 

	 int[] a = {1,2,3,4,5};
	 
	 int[] b = new int[2];
	 int[] c = new int[3];
	 
	 System.arraycopy(a, 0, b, 0, 2); // b will be {1,2}
	 System.arraycopy(a, 2, c, 0, 3); // c will be {3,4,5}



  [1]: http://download.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/lang/System.html#arraycopy%28java.lang.Object,%20int,%20java.lang.Object,%20int,%20int%29

You&#39;ll want to do something that makes use of [List.subList(int, int)][1] views rather than copying each sublist. To do this really easily, use [Guava][2]&#39;s [Lists.partition(List, int)][3] method:

    List&lt;Foo&gt; foos = ...
    for (List&lt;Foo&gt; partition : Lists.partition(foos, n)) {
      // do something with partition
    }

Note that this, like many things, isn&#39;t very efficient with a `List` that isn&#39;t `RandomAccess` (such as a `LinkedList`).

