I have resolved my issue.

As **M. Deinum** stated in his comments, it was a pure Spring Configuration issue.

The fact is that during the refactoring of the legacy code, the following block of code made its way into a java Spring Configuration file.

    @Bean
      MethodInvokingFactoryBean methodInvokingFactoryBean(DefaultSecurityManager securityManager)
      {
        MethodInvokingFactoryBean methodInvokingFactoryBean = new MethodInvokingFactoryBean();
    
        methodInvokingFactoryBean.setStaticMethod(&quot;org.apache.shiro.SecurityUtils.setSecurityManager&quot;);
        methodInvokingFactoryBean.setArguments(securityManager);
    
        return methodInvokingFactoryBean;
      }

My DefaultSecurityManager is dependent on my Service where my `@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)` is.

This block of code disrupts the normal flow/init of Spring and the `@Transactional` annotation get ignored.

This explains why during Spring init my method is not identified as transactional and no new transaction is started when the method is called.

Replacing the wrong block of code by a simple call to the correct Set method does resolve the issue

    SecurityUtils.setSecurityManager(result);

Thank you all for your time and help.

